$$ HOUSE-PRICE-PREDICTIONS $$¶

Introduction:¶

In this notebook we will predict the house prices located in Ames, Iowa.

The biggest challenge in this project is the number of columns. There are total of 81 columns in the training dataset out of which 79 columns just contains the features of the houses.

Let's start this project and make our predictions.

Problem Statement:¶

The main goal of the project is to Develope a supervised machine learning model(Regression) to predict the house price accurately with the help of the given data. The data has been split into two groups, a training set and test set. I will use train set to build regression model to generate predictions for the test set.

File descriptions¶

train_data.csv - the training set

test_data.csv - the test set

Observation: Missing data in the dataset

In datatype object:

  • Missing data in 15 Columns
  • Missing data > 80% in 4 Columns include Alley, PoolQC, Fence and MiscFeature
  • Missing data > 45% in Column FireplaceQC

In datatype numerics (integers + float):

  • Missing data only in 3 Coulmns
  • Missing data < 20% in Column LotFrontage
  • Missing data < 6% in Column GarangeYrBlt
  • Missing data < 1% in Column MasVnrArea

Very less number of Columns with missing values.

Columns having datatype object have high percentage of missing values as compared to columns with datatype intergers and float.

Due to huge data gap, Alley, PoolQC, Fence and MiscFeature cloumns have been deleted from the dataset

# function for checking accuracy:

def predict_score(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    
    results = {}
    
    # Fit the model to the training data:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # predict on the testing data:
    pred = model.predict(X_test)
        
    results['r2_score'] = r2_score(y_test, pred)
    results['mean_squared_error'] = mean_squared_error(pred, y_test)
    results['mean_absolute_error'] = mean_absolute_error(y_test, pred)
        
    return results

Model Refinement / Hyperparameter Tuning:¶

We will fine tune our model using grid search technique. Where we will need to tell which hyper parameters we want to experiment and what values to try out, and grid search technique will evaluate all the possible combination of hyper parameters values, using cross validation.

In [76]:
gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor()

gbr.fit(X_train, y_train)


n_estimators = [100, 200, 300]
max_features = [25, 45, 50]
max_depth = [15, 13, 18]
max_leaf_nodes = [8, 10, 13]


param_grid = { 'n_estimators': n_estimators,
                'max_features': max_features,
                'max_depth': max_depth,
                'max_leaf_nodes': max_leaf_nodes }

search = GridSearchCV(estimator = gbr, param_grid = param_grid, cv = 5, n_jobs = -1)
search.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = search.predict(X_test)
print(r2_score(y_test, y_pred))

Conclusion:¶

We have started the problem by exploring the data and then cleaning and after the preprocessing, we have ended with the model building step.

After going through a bunch of processes, we have successfully built and evaluated different types of regression models in python also, choosing the best model for our given dataset.

But, this won’t stop here. Each and every model we built have their own statistical and mathematical concepts. The reason why we have chosen these these models is because of its popularity.

There are also many other different linear regression models like the Poisson regression model, Boosted decision tree model, Decision tree model, and so on.

This model can also be used to predict the house prices in any geographic location by fine tuning the features and parameters.

Improvement:¶

I think I got good results for the prediction model.

I completely understood the data provided by Kaggle.

I believe that the idea of improving the data collection or fixing issues related with the missing data or NaNs would be really helpful.

In my opinion, I think that we can get great insights from this data set and great prediction models might be also built to solve problems statements associated with this data set.

Reflection:¶

I thoroughly enjoyed working on this project which allowed me to polish my skills in Data Preprocessing and Modeling.

The most difficult part in my opinion was understanding the dataset.

The Preprocessing step was the longest and most challenging part to complete.

The Dataset itself is inspiring.
